<br>
If I'm remembering the story correctly, Glushko, Chelomei, and Korolev were the Big 3.  There was a history, though, between Glushko and Korolev.  I don't know if I have all the details straight, but I believe Glushko &quot;fingered&quot; Korolev during one of Stalin's purges and Korolev went into the Gulag system.  After a long series of events, Korolev established his own design bureau, in competition with I think two others, Chelomei's being one of them.  Glushko began developing engines that used hypergolic propellents, which were eventually used by Chelomei in the Proton.  Korolev did not care for hypergolic propellents -- being ferociously toxic, he felt they were too dangerous.<br>
<br>
There are a lot of particulars that I'm sure I'm not remembering, but the drift here is that the conflict between design bureaus and the Byzantine nature of Soviet politics hurt them enormously.  It wasn't until 1964 that the Soviets actually committed themselves to a lunar landing mission, and America was already three years ahead of them.  The miracle is that, considering all the internal obstacles, their program did as well as it did. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 653<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/5/03 1:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if the Russians won the moon race?</span><hr size=1> I think I got some of my facts I wrong, it was probably Glushko who developed the engines but wasn't able to convince the higher ups to go with his plans for a lunar rocket.  It's an incredible story how Korolev went through the gulags, had his health permanently damaged, and still came back to lead the USSR in its space endeavours.  If Korolev hadn't died when he did there's a lot of speculation that the Soviets might have still made it to the moon although not first.  He apparently had a lot of improvements to the N-1 on the drawing board that might have worked but Glushko pretty much canned all of the work in progress that Korolev had left behind.  I don't think Glushko had Korolev's idealism when it came to exploring the moon and beyond.  I think Korolev would have kept pushing for manned missions to the Moon and Mars had he lived longer.     <p></p><i></i></td><